	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>USDA review of EU fruit-and-vegetable trade arrangements </h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> A new USDA report notes that the EU is ‘the world’s largest importer of fruits and vegetables’ and that over ‘70% of EU fruit-and-vegetable imports are from countries benefiting from preferential treatment for some portion of that trade’ Only nine countries trade fruit and vegetables into the EU under MFN tariffs (China, Taiwan, Japan, South Korea, Singapore, Hong Kong, Australia, New Zealand and Canada).</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> Cotonou and EBA preferences are reported as ‘the most valuable preferences’, but the EU system creates ‘a mosaic of tariffs, quotas and other import restrictions that vary considerably among products and among preferred partners which makes analysis impossibly complex’. However such arrangements are an ‘integral part of the management of EU imports’ under the fruit-and-vegetable regime of the CAP. The report reviews each of the arrangements affecting fruit-and-vegetable imports into the EU in turn: the regime ‘establishes minimum price requirements or restricts imports through quotas associated with various preferential arrangements’, and these may vary seasonally to provide higher protection at times of peak EU production. The whole regime requires ‘very high MFN tariffs’, which however apply to only these nine countries.</p><p> The following fruits and vegetables are classified as sensitive: apples; pears; grapes; melons; strawberries; onions; cauliflower; cabbage; celery; carrots; cucumbers; peas; artichokes; mushrooms; new potatoes; asparagus; eggplant; sweet peppers; spinach and tomatoes. Some nuts are also defined as sensitive including: pecan nuts, almonds, hazelnuts and chestnuts. For all these products some levels of duties are maintained under the EU’s GSP regime. Indeed, tomatoes, cucumbers, banana and pecan nuts are not covered by the GSP regime and so receive no duty reductions under GSP arrangements.</p><p> Under the Cotonou Agreement the ‘tariff reductions provided the ACP countries outside of quotas by the EU are generally larger than those provided by the EU’s GSP’. In addition under Cotonou ‘tariff reductions are provided for many products not covered by the GSP’. Furthermore ‘some ACP tariff reductions are considerably larger than those provided by the EU’s basic GSP’, although they are still subject to quota restrictions. However ‘as with the basic GSP, ACP reductions generally are for ad valorem tariffs only, often leaving specific tariffs in effect’.</p><p> The report maintains that ‘the EBA is a major departure in EU agricultural trading relationships because it eliminates the mechanisms by which the CAP manages sensitive imports, preventing low-priced imports from undermining internal EU prices’. However given the limited export potential of LDCs this is likely to have little effect on the EU fruit-and-vegetable sector (except for bananas), unless all domestic production is diverted for export, with domestic needs being met by imports and substantial new investment is attracted into production of fruit and vegetables in LDCs.</p><p> On the down-side the report notes the difficulties LDCs and ACP countries will face as a result of EU traceability regulations which require ‘exporters to trace their product back to the plot and seed it came from’. Indeed LDC fruit-and-vegetable exports to the EU declined slightly during the 2001-2003 period (from US$109 million to US$101 million). This however may be simply a result of exchange-rate movements between the US dollar and the euro. While new investments in meeting EU standards have been made (with EU assistance) ‘it remains to be seen whether sufficient investments will be forthcoming because of the added costs that the new rules imply for exporters’.</p><p> The report explains how quota arrangements in the fruit-and-vegetable sector are managed through import licences which are granted to ‘EU companies, leaving the exporting countries to compete for import contracts’. This may limit the benefits that ACP countries gain from the trade preferences they enjoy.</p><p> ACP countries account for about 13% of EU fruit-and-vegetable imports and LDCs a further 1%. The largest source of supply is from GSP beneficiaries (38%); the USA provides 10%, Mediterranean countries and other European countries 9% each, Turkey 3% (exclusively processed products), and other MFN beneficiaries 9%. 8% traditionally came from countries which have now acceded to the EU.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.ers.usda.gov/publications/VGS/Jul04/vgs30301/vgs30301.pdf" target="_self">USDA Economic Research Service </a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The fact that 70% of EU fruit-and-vegetable imports enter the EU market under some kind of preferential arrangement, means that in looking at the impact of the possible loss of current Cotonou trade preferences, this will need to be calculated not with reference to the MFN duty, but with reference to the actual duties charged on the particular products exported by competitors of ACP countries. This is particularly the case for sensitive fruit and vegetables where often some level of GSP duty is maintained (GSP would be the alternative regime for non-LDC ACP countries).</p><p> The EU’s willingness to propose the EBA, which involves the abandonment of ‘the mechanisms by which the CAP manages sensitive imports’ needs to be seen against the background of the progress made in shifting agricultural support away from price support to direct aid to farmers. This is a policy change which is allowing EU market prices to fall, thereby doing away with the need for high levels of tariff protection, and undermining the value of preferential access to the EU market.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

